Implement a JavaScript `EventEmitter` class with the following methods:
- `on(event, listener)` — register a listener for an event
- `off(event, listener)` — remove a specific listener
- `emit(event, ...args)` — call all listeners for an event (and wildcard '*' listeners)
- `once(event, listener)` — register a listener that fires only once

Wildcard '*' listeners receive the event name as the first argument, followed by the emitted args.

Include this test code at the end:

const emitter = new EventEmitter();
const results = [];

emitter.on('data', (val) => results.push('data:' + val));
emitter.once('data', (val) => results.push('once:' + val));
emitter.on('*', (event, val) => results.push('wild:' + event + ':' + val));

emitter.emit('data', 'first');
emitter.emit('data', 'second');
emitter.emit('other', 'third');

const handler = (val) => results.push('temp:' + val);
emitter.on('data', handler);
emitter.emit('data', 'fourth');
emitter.off('data', handler);
emitter.emit('data', 'fifth');

console.log(results.join('\n'));
